Head Squared Preview (Release Date, Specs & Everything We ...
  URL: https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/
  Estimated Specifications ; Head size, 100 sq in (estimated) ; Unstrung weight, 295g ; Balance, 300mm (extremely head-light) ; Swing weight, 268 ( ...

  --- Content ---
  [Skip to content](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#content)
  
  ![Head Squared Blog](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Head-Squared-Blog-1024x427.webp)
  
  * * *
  
  Head has been quietly building hype around something properly different. The Squared is not just another refresh of an existing line. It’s an entirely new racket family, separate from the Speed, Gravity, Prestige, Extreme, Boom and Radical ranges that make up Head’s current lineup.
  
  Images first appeared online in mid-2025, and the tennis community has been speculating ever since. What we know so far paints a picture of a racket designed to prioritise comfort, forgiveness and easy power, potentially giving Head a direct answer to the Wilson Clash, which has dominated that segment of the market for years.
  
  Here’s everything we’ve been able to piece together ahead of the expected launch.
  
  Table Of Contents
  
  01. [What Makes the Squared Different?](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#what-makes-the-squared-different)
  02. [Estimated Specifications](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#estimated-specifications)
  03. [Who Is the Squared Designed For?](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#who-is-the-squared-designed-for)
  04. [How Does It Compare to the Wilson Clash?](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#how-does-it-compare-to-the-wilson-clash)
  05. [Where Does Squared Fit in Head's Lineup?](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#where-does-squared-fit-in-heads-lineup)
  06. [String Considerations](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#string-considerations)
  07. [Expected Release Date and Pricing](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#expected-release-date-and-pricing)
  08. [What We're Watching For](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#what-were-watching-for)
  09. [Complete Your Setup](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#complete-your-setup)
  10. [Early Verdict](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#early-verdict)
  11. [More Reviews From TGG](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/head-squared-review/#more-reviews-from-tgg)
  
  ## What Makes the Squared Different?
  
  The most immediately obvious difference is the string bed. Rather than the conventional oval drilling pattern found on virtually every other racket, the Squared features a more rounded hoop that produces a square-shaped grid in the centre of the string bed. It’s a striking visual departure and, more importantly, it’s designed to deliver a more consistent hitting sensation across a wider area of the face.
  
  Think of it this way. On a traditional racket, the sweet spot is relatively concentrated in the middle of the string bed. Miss the centre by a couple of centimetres and you feel it immediately, both in the vibration through your arm and in where the ball actually goes. The Squared’s design aims to reduce that inconsistency, making off-centre hits feel closer to pure strikes.
  
  This is a big deal for recreational and [intermediate players](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/best-intermediate-tennis-rackets/) who don’t always find the sweet spot on every ball. It’s also potentially significant for anyone dealing with arm problems, since harsh vibrations from mishits are a major contributor to tennis elbow.
  
  ## Estimated Specifications
  
  Head hasn’t officially confirmed full specifications, so take these with a degree of caution. They’re based on early measurements from independent testers who have had access to what appears to be the standard MP model.
  
  | Specification | Estimated Value |
  | --- | --- |
  | Head size | 100 sq in (estimated) |
  | Unstrung weight | 295g |
  | Balance | 300mm (extremely head-light) |
  | Swing weight | 268 (unstrung) |
  | Stiffness | 64 RA (unstrung) |
  | String pattern | TBC |
  | Length | Standard (27 inches) |
  
  A few things immediately stand out here.
  
  The balance is remarkably head-light at 300mm. To put that in context, most modern rackets sit somewhere between 315mm and 330mm. A 300mm balance is, by some accounts, the most head-light measurement currently available on the market. This should make the Squared feel incredibly fast to swing and very easy on the wrist, particularly for players who tend to take shorter, more compact swings.
  
  The swing weight of 268 (unstrung) is also very low. Stringing typically adds around 30 points, which would bring it to roughly 298 strung. For comparison, the [Head Speed MP](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/recommends/head-speed-mp/ "Head Speed MP") 2026 sits around 325 strung. A lower swing weight makes the racket easier to manoeuvre but could sacrifice some stability against heavy balls. It’s a trade-off that favours accessibility over raw plow-through.
  
  The stiffness of 64 RA (dropping to around 61 strung) puts the Squared in comfortable territory without being extremely flexy. It’s softer than something like a [Pure Drive](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/recommends/babolat-pure-drive/ "Babolat Pure Drive") but firmer than the Wilson Clash v3, which sits at 54 RA. This suggests Head is aiming for a balance between comfort and responsiveness rather than going all-in on flexibility.
  
  ## Who Is the Squared Designed For?
  
  Based on everything we’ve seen so far, the Squared appears to be targeting a few specific player profiles.
  
  **Recreational players** who want a racket that’s forgiving and easy to swing will likely find the Squared very appealing. The combination of light weight, head-light balance and an expanded sweet spot ticks all the boxes for players who play once or twice a week and don’t want to fight their equipment.
  
  **Older players and those returning to the sport** could benefit enormously from the low swing weight and comfort-oriented design. If you’ve picked tennis back up after years away, or you’re finding your current racket increasingly tiring during longer sessions, this kind of specification profile makes a lot of sense.
  
  **Players dealing with arm issues** should pay attention. The head-light balance reduces strain on the wrist and elbow, while the flexible-ish frame and expanded sweet spot should minimise the harsh vibrations that aggravate existing injuries.
  
  **Coaches and hitting partners** who spend hours on court feeding balls will appreciate a racket that doesn’t beat up their arm over a full day of sessions.
  
  Where it probably won’t suit is [advanced players](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/best-advanced-tennis-rackets/) who generate significant racket head speed and need a frame that can handle incoming pace without twisting. The very low swing weight could feel unstable when absorbing heavy balls, and the extremely head-light balance might lack the mass through contact that competitive players demand.
  
  That said, it’s worth reserving final judgement until full play-test reports are available. Rackets can surprise you. The Clash was written off by many serious players initially and ended up being adopted by a decent number of competitive club players who valued the comfort.
  
  ## How Does It Compare to the Wilson Clash?
  
  This is the obvious comparison and one that Head has seemingly invited. The Clash has owned the comfort and forgiveness segment since its launch, and the Squared looks like a direct attempt to offer an alternative.
  
  On paper, the key differences are:
  
  The Clash v3 is softer (54 RA versus the Squared’s estimated 61 strung), meaning it will pocket the ball more and feel more dampened on contact. Players who love that distinctive Clash “flex” may find the Squared slightly firmer.
  
  The Squared appears to be lighter and more head-light than the [Clash 100](https://tidd.ly/47hhj8o "Wilson Clash 100"), which comes in at 295g unstrung with a 310mm balance. That 10mm difference in balance is significant and should make the Squared noticeably quicker to swing.
  
  The unique string bed design on the Squared is something the Clash simply doesn’t offer. If the squared drilling pattern does expand the effective sweet spot as intended, this could be the Squared’s strongest selling point.
  
  Both rackets seem aimed at a similar demographic. If you’re currently happy with a Clash, the Squared is worth demoing when it becomes available. If you’ve always felt the Clash was a touch too heavy or sluggish for your taste, the Squared’s lighter, faster profile might be exactly what you’re after.
  
  ## Where Does Squared Fit in Head’s Lineup?
  
  Head currently runs one of the broadest racket ranges in tennis. The Speed line handles the all-round market. The Prestige covers control-oriented players. The Extreme is for spin enthusiasts. The Gravity targets comfort with control. The Boom offers power and spin for younger players. And the Radical sits as a versatile mid-range option.
  
  The Squared fills a gap that the Gravity partially addresses but doesn’t fully commit to. While the Gravity is comfortable, it’s still firmly a performance racket with specifications that demand reasonable technique. The Squared goes further down the accessibility route, with that ultra-low swing weight and extreme head-light balance creating something built entirely around ease of use rather than performance metrics.
  
  For [beginners](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/best-tennis-rackets-for-beginners/), this could end up being one of the better Head options. Previously, the Instinct line served this market, but the Squared appears to offer a more sophisticated approach to the same problem of making tennis more enjoyable for people who aren’t hitting five days a week.
  
  ## String Considerations
  
  Without confirmed string pattern details, it’s difficult to make definitive [string recommendations](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/the-complete-guide-to-tennis-strings/). However, based on the specification profile, a few general principles apply.
  
  A racket this light and head-light will benefit from strings that add some mass and stability to the head. A multifilament at moderate tension (around 22-24 kg) would complement the comfort-oriented design and add to the arm-friendly characteristics. Something like the Wilson NXT or Tecnifibre X-One Biphase would be a natural pairing.
  
  If you prefer polyester, going with a softer poly at a lower tension (around 20-22 kg) would avoid making the string bed feel too board-like. With the low swing weight, you don’t want to add unnecessary stiffness that your arm will have to absorb.
  
  Hybrid setups with a poly main and multifilament cross could also work well, giving you a bit of durability and spin potential from the mains with added comfort from the crosses.
  
  ## Expected Release Date and Pricing
  
  No official release date has been confirmed by Head. Based on the timeline of leaked images appearing in mid-2025 and the typical cycle for Head product launches, most industry watchers expect availability in the first half of 2026, possibly around May.
  
  Pricing is also unconfirmed. Looking at Head’s current lineup, the [Gravity MP](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/recommends/head-gravity-mp/ "Head Gravity MP") retails at around £220 and the [Boom MP](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/recommends/head-boom-mp/ "Head Boom MP") at roughly £200. The Squared will likely fall somewhere in that range, though the entirely new construction could push it slightly higher. We’d estimate somewhere between £200 and £240, but that’s a guess at this stage.
  
  It’s also unclear how many models will be in the range at launch. Head typically releases families with an MP, Pro and Team/Lite variant. Given the Squared’s recreational positioning, an MP and a lighter Team model would make the most sense, but we’ll have to wait for the official announcement.
  
  ## What We’re Watching For
  
  A few key questions remain unanswered that will determine whether the Squared is worth the hype or just another comfort racket.
  
  **Stability under pressure.** That 268 swing weight is very low. The big unknown is whether the Squared can handle pace from the other side of the net without feeling like it’s being pushed around. Head’s Graphene technology has historically done a good job of adding stability without adding weight, so there’s reason to be cautiously optimistic.
  
  **The string bed innovation.** The squared drilling pattern is the headline feature. If it delivers a noticeably larger effective sweet spot, that’s a meaningful advancement. If the difference is marginal, the Squared loses its most compelling differentiator.
  
  **Build quality of the new material.** Early reports mention a different material composition for improved feel and comfort. How this translates to durability and long-term performance will matter, particularly at the likely price point.
  
  **Tour adoption.** This probably won’t be a tour racket in its stock form, but if Head can get a few recognisable players to use a modified version, it will do wonders for the Squared’s credibility. The Clash benefited enormously from appearing on the professional circuit, even in heavily customised form.
  
  ## Complete Your Setup
  
  If you’re planning to try the Head Squared when it launches, it’s worth thinking about the rest of your kit too. The right [tennis shoes](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/best-tennis-shoes/) make a bigger difference to your movement and comfort than most players realise, and pairing a comfort-focused racket with the wrong footwear somewhat defeats the purpose.
  
  A decent [tennis bag](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/best-tennis-bags/) is also worth considering if you’re investing in new equipment. Proper racket compartments with thermal lining will protect your strings and frame from temperature damage, particularly during summer months.
  
  And if you’re serious about improving alongside your new racket, a [ball machine](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/best-tennis-ball-machines/) can accelerate your development faster than almost anything else. Repetition is how you groove technique, and feeding yourself [quality balls](https://tennisgearguide.co.uk/best-tennis-balls/) through a machine lets you hit hundreds of forehands without needing a hitting partner.
  
  ## Early Verdict
  
  It’s too early to pass definitive judgement on a racket that hasn’t officially launched yet. But the Head Squared looks like an interesting addition to the market rather than just another line extension.
  
  The unique string bed design, extreme head-light balance and comfort-first philosophy suggest Head is trying to solve a real problem rather than just refreshing an existing product. Whether it pulls players away from the established Clash, or carves out its own niche among recreational and returning players, will depend on how well the technology translates from concept to court.
  
  We’ll update this article with full play-test impressions and a detailed review once we get our hands on the production model. In the meantime, if you’re currently shopping for a racket and can afford to wait a few months, the Squared is definitely worth holding out for, at least to demo before making a final decision.
  
