  Yes to a light racquet where a majority of the mass is in the middle (that might be what gives it its stability). Finally! So much better for volleying and rushing the net. Feels like every manufacturer makes the same racquet that is super polarized and can't handle a volley. Headlight is great for people with wrist problems/weakness. I think the Clash is the only racquet that occupies the space with a HL balance more than 32cm (and under 330+g).
  
  [![naturalexponent](https://tt.tennis-warehouse.com/data/avatars/m/11/11848.jpg?1768943528)](https://tt.tennis-warehouse.com/index.php?members/naturalexponent.11848/)
  
  #### [naturalexponent](https://tt.tennis-warehouse.com/index.php?members/naturalexponent.11848/)
  
  ##### Legend
  
  Quick thoughts after a few tiebreaks + one set of play.
  
  GREAT on serve. With the light weight and head light balance, you can really move it overhead with ease.
  
  On softer shots/mini tennis, the impression I get is that it's like if you took concentrated all of Head's auxetic feel across its lines and concentrated it and poured it into one mold, you'd end up with the Squared. It's just so... auxetic-y.
  
  When you speed up and start really swinging the racquet, there's this sensation that the racquet stiffens up on impact.
  
  Feels a bit shaky at net as a combination of the two foregoing points.
  
  I played best with this thing immediately after I was grooved with my usual or a heavier racquet because then you sort of have your normal stroke mechanics applied to a lighter, more forgiving racquet so you can blast some serves and returns. After about a game or two, bad habits started creeping in, or I just lost kind of the kinesthetic sense of where the racquet was and what it was doing because it's so light/headlight.
  
  On to the next user this week.
  
